The Bank of Industry (BoI) reported that it disbursed N234 billion to 10,145 enterprises, thus facilitating the creating of an estimated one million direct and indirect jobs in 2019 financial year. This is even as the development finance institution also recorded a profit of N39.33 billion during the period. The 2019 financial accounts of the Bank also indicated a total equity as at year ended 2019 was N293.09 billion showing a 13.4% increase over 2018 position of N258.24 billion. Profit Before Tax of the group grew to N39.33 billion, marking a year-on-year growth of 7.2% over N36.66 billion of 2018. The increase in profitability is as a result of improvement in loan book, as well as the efficient management of the group’s other assets and liabilities. Despite a slow start in the first quarter of the year due to the build-up to the 2019 general elections, loans and advances grew by 16.7% from N634.11billion in 2018 to N740.03 billion in 2019. Interest Income and Interest Expense increased by 20% and 54% on a year-on-year basis due to increase in loan book as well as the impact of borrowings (full year impact on the interest expense in 2019, while 2018 impact was for 6months). The disbursement to the Micro, Small and Medium Enterprises (MSME) segment increased from N33.9 billion in 2018 to N53.0 billion in 2019, representing a remarkable 56.3% year-on-year growth. The bank also consolidated its role as the managing partner of one of the Federal Government’s Social Investment Programmes, Government Enterprise and Empowerment Programme (GEEP). N8.2 billion was disbursed to beneficiaries in 2019, thus bringing the total disbursed amount since inception to N36.9 billion to 2.3 million beneficiaries nationwide. BoI records N39.33bn profit, disburses N234bn to 10,145 enterprises BoI records N39.33b profit, disburses N234 billion to 10,145 enterprises FCMB sustains performance with N177.4bn revenue, achieves 73% profit increase